text:
Microspherophakia is a rare &lt;a href="Congenital%20disorder"&gt;congenital&lt;/a&gt; &lt;a href="recessive"&gt;autosomal recessive&lt;/a&gt; condition where the &lt;a href="Lens%20%28anatomy%29"&gt;lens&lt;/a&gt; of the eye is smaller than normal and spherically shaped. This condition may be associated with a number of disorders including &lt;a href="Anterior%20segment%20mesenchymal%20dysgenesis"&gt;Peter's anomaly&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="Marfan%20syndrome"&gt;Marfan syndrome&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="Weill%E2%80%93Marchesani%20syndrome"&gt;Weill–Marchesani syndrome&lt;/a&gt;. The spherical shape is caused by an underdeveloped &lt;a href="zonule%20of%20Zinn"&gt;zonule of Zinn&lt;/a&gt;, which doesn't exert enough force on the lens to make it form the usual oval shape. It is a result of a &lt;a href="Zygosity%23Homozygous"&gt;homozygous&lt;/a&gt; mutation to the LTBP2 gene.
